---
title: Classic Tuna Sandwiches with Baby Lettuce Salad & Honey Dijon Dressing
description: It’s the simple things, isn’t it? The smell after a spring rain, a cozy nap on the couch, and a perfect tuna sandwich. Complicated? No. Profoundly satisfying? Yes! Between these two lucky slices of sourdough bread is tuna mixed with crunchy celery, chopped pickle, and a dollop of creamy mayo. You’ll serve your sandwich with a green side salad tossed in a tangy honey Dijon dressing for a simple pleasure that’s ready in just 10 minutes.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/classic-tuna-sandwiches-fd4134d1.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/classic-tuna-sandwiches-64107f24526c341c5406c2c5-4bf466e1.pdf
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/classic-tuna-sandwiches-64107f24526c341c5406c2c5
author: Michelle Doll Olson
time required: 10 minutes
servings: 2
course: main course
cuisine: North America
nutrition:
  calories: 780 kcal
  fat: 47 g
  saturated fat: 7 g
  carbohydrates: 62 g
  sugar: 9 g
  protein: 26 g
  fiber: 3 g
  sodium: 1520 mg
---

Toast @sourdough bread{4%slices} in a #toaster{} until golden brown.

Wash and dry @celery{1}, @sliced dill pickle{1}, and @baby lettuce{1}.

Finely dice half the celery (all for 4 servings). Finely chop half the pickle
(all for 4). Trim and discard root end from lettuce; separate leaves. Reserve
a whole leaf for each sandwich; chop the rest into bite-size pieces.

Open and drain @tuna{5.6%ounce}, squeezing out any excess liquid.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine tuna, diced celery, @mayonnaise{4%tablespoon}, a
big pinch of @salt{pinch}, @pepper{to taste}, and as much chopped pickle as
you like.

In a #large bowl{}, toss together chopped lettuce, @honey Dijon dressing{1.5%ounce}, a
drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon}, and salt and pepper to taste.

On a #cutting board{}, spread tuna mixture on half the bread slices. Top with
a lettuce leaf and remaining bread slices; halve sandwiches on a diagonal.

Divide sandwiches between plates. Serve with salad on the side.

> It's the simple things, isn't it? The smell after a spring rain, a cozy nap
> on the couch, and a perfect tuna sandwich. Complicated? No. Profoundly
> satisfying? Yes! Between these two lucky slices of sourdough bread is tuna
> mixed with crunchy celery, chopped pickle, and a dollop of creamy mayo. You'll
> serve your sandwich with a green side salad tossed in a tangy honey Dijon
> dressing for a simple pleasure that's ready in just 10 minutes.